data.content:
**MSTest Collection Assertions**

Your test works but produces unhelpful failure messages (just "Assert.IsTrue failed"). MSTest provides dedicated collection and assertion APIs:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — on failure it shows *both* values, unlike `Assert.IsTrue(x == 3)` which just says "false"
- **Message parameters** — add context strings to `Assert.IsTrue` calls so failures are diagnosable
- **`Assert.AreEqual(3, ...)` replaces both** the `Count > 0` and `Count == 3` checks
- **`users.Any(...)` over `Single(...) != null`** — `Single` throws if not found, masking the real assertion

**Other useful patterns:**

```csharp
// Assert exact elements (order-sensitive)
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);

// Assert same elements, any order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);

// Assert all items satisfy a condition
CollectionAssert.AllAreSatisfied(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));

// Assert a specific item exists
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
```

`CollectionAssert` gives you richer diagnostics out of the box compared to manual LINQ + `Assert.IsTrue`.
